properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 12 at 4:43PM CST by NWS Green Bay WI
properties.description:
An arctic cold front was dropping south across central into far
northeast Wisconsin early this evening, bringing a round of light
snow. Most locations should see an inch or two of snow before
tapering off to scattered flurries later this evening or on early
Thursday morning. The combination of the falling snow, along with
melting snow on pavement surfaces and falling air temperatures
well below freezing could lead to a flash freeze this evening.
Gusty northerly winds may also create some areas of blowing and
drifting snow.

Overnight, temperatures are expected to fall to 5 below to 5 above
zero. The combination of the cold temperatures and gusty northerly
winds will produce wind chill readings in the 10 below to 20
below zero range late tonight into Thursday morning. Wind chill
readings this low can produce frost bite in 30 minutes.

Allow extra travel time if you will be driving this evening as
roads will be slippery due to ice and snow. If venturing outdoors
overnight, wear layers of clothing along with a hat and gloves to
protect yourself from the cold.

NWSheadline: HAZARDOUS TRAVEL CONDITIONS EXPECTED THIS EVENING FOLLOWED BY COLD WIND CHILLS OVERNIGHT
